answers.body_markdown:
When we say a simple for loop has a time complexity of O(N), we mean that the time it takes to execute the loop depends on the input size of N. For instance

    function doLoop(n) {
         let i = 0;
         while (i &lt; n) {
             console.log(&#39;doing stuff&#39;);
             i++;
         }


In that function, if we pass 2, our loop executes twice and if we pass 100 it&#39;ll run 100 times, etc. 


In your loop- we&#39;re not passing any input at all. The loop will ALWAYS execute exactly 10 times. So its O(10). Typically, when expressing Big O notation, we ignore constant values, and since O(10) =&gt; 10 * O(1); your for loop is O(1), a constant time loop that does not depend on the size of any input variables.

